# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pi-calculus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] In computer science, the **ambient calculus** is a process calculus devised by Luca Cardelli and Andrew D.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] Gordon in 1998, and used to describe and theorise about concurrent systems that include *mobility*.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] Here *mobility* means both computation carried out on mobile devices (*i.e.* networks that have a dynamic topology), and mobile computation (*i.e.* executable code that is able to move around the network).
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] The ambient calculus provides a unified framework for modeling both kinds of mobility.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] It is used to model interactions in such concurrent systems as the Internet.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] Since its inception, the ambient calculus has grown into a family of closely related ambient calculi.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] The fundamental primitive of the ambient calculus is the **ambient**.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] An ambient is informally defined as a *bounded* place in which computation can occur.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] The notion of boundaries is considered key to representing mobility, since a boundary defines a contained computational agent that can be moved in its entirety.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] Computation is represented as the crossing of boundaries, *i.e.* the movement of ambients.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] The ambient calculus provides a reduction semantics that formally defines what the results of these operations are.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] Communication *within* (*i.e.* local to) an ambient is anonymous and asynchronous.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] Output actions release names or capabilities into the surrounding ambient.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] Input actions capture a value from the ambient, and bind it to a variable.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] *Non-local* I/O can be represented in terms of these local communications actions by a variety of means.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] One approach is to use mobile “messenger” agents that carry a message from one ambient to another (using the capabilities described above).
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] Another approach is to emulate channel-based communications by modeling a channel in terms of ambients and operations on those ambients.
[src:pi-calculus/ambient-calculus] The three basic ambient primitives, namely **in**, **out**, and **open** are expressive enough to simulate name-passing channels in the π-calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] In computer science, **concurrency** refers to the ability of a system to execute multiple tasks through simultaneous execution or time-sharing (context switching), sharing resources and managing interactions.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Because computations in a concurrent system can interact with each other while being executed, the number of possible execution paths in the system can be extremely large, and the resulting outcome can be indeterminate.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Concurrent use of shared resources can be a source of indeterminacy, leading to issues such as deadlocks, and resource starvation.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Design of concurrent systems often entails finding reliable techniques for coordinating their execution, data exchange, memory allocation, and execution scheduling to minimize response time and maximize throughput.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Concurrency theory has been an active field of research in theoretical computer science.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] One of the first proposals was Carl Adam Petri's seminal work on Petri nets in the early 1960s.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] In the years since, a wide variety of formalisms have been developed for modeling and reasoning about concurrency.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Some of these models of concurrency are primarily intended to support reasoning and specification, while others can be used through the entire development cycle, including design, implementation, proof, testing, and simulation of concurrent systems.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Some of these are based on message passing, while others have different mechanisms for concurrency.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] The proliferation of different models of concurrency has motivated some researchers to develop ways to unify these different theoretical models.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] The Concurrency Representation Theorem in the actor model provides a fairly general way to represent concurrent systems that are closed in the sense that they do not receive communications from outside.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] In this way, S can be mathematically characterized in terms of all its possible behaviors.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Various types of temporal logic can be used to help reason about concurrent systems.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Some of these logics, such as linear temporal logic and computation tree logic, allow assertions to be made about the sequences of states that a concurrent system can pass through.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Others, such as action computational tree logic, Hennessy–Milner logic, and Lamport's temporal logic of actions, build their assertions from sequences of *actions* (changes in state).
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] The principal application of these logics is in writing specifications for concurrent systems.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Concurrent programming encompasses programming languages and algorithms used to implement concurrent systems.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Concurrent programming is usually considered to be more general than parallel programming because it can involve arbitrary and dynamic patterns of communication and interaction, whereas parallel systems generally have a predefined and well-structured communications pattern.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] The base goals of concurrent programming include *correctness*, *performance* and *robustness*.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Concurrent systems such as Operating systems and Database management systems are generally designed to operate indefinitely, including automatic recovery from failure, and not terminate unexpectedly (see Concurrency control).
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Some concurrent systems implement a form of transparent concurrency, in which concurrent computational entities may compete for and share a single resource, but the complexities of this competition and sharing are shielded from the programmer.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Because they use shared resources, concurrent systems in general require the inclusion of some kind of arbiter somewhere in their implementation (often in the underlying hardware), to control access to those resources.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] The use of arbiters introduces the possibility of indeterminacy in concurrent computation which has major implications for practice including correctness and performance.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] For example, arbitration introduces unbounded nondeterminism which raises issues with model checking because it causes explosion in the state space and can even cause models to have an infinite number of states.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] Some concurrent programming models include coprocesses and deterministic concurrency.
[src:pi-calculus/concurrency-computer-science] In these models, threads of control explicitly yield their timeslices, either to the system or to another process.
[src:pi-calculus/join-calculus] The **join-calculus** is a process calculus developed at INRIA.
[src:pi-calculus/join-calculus] The join-calculus was developed to provide a formal basis for the design of distributed programming languages, and therefore intentionally avoids communication constructs found in other process calculi, such as rendezvous communications, which are difficult to implement in a distributed setting.
[src:pi-calculus/join-calculus] Despite this limitation, the join-calculus is as expressive as the full π-calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/join-calculus] Encodings of the π-calculus in the join-calculus, and vice versa, have been demonstrated.
[src:pi-calculus/join-calculus] However, as a language for programming, the join-calculus offers at least one convenience over the π-calculus — namely the use of *multi-way join patterns*, the ability to match against messages from multiple channels simultaneously.
[src:pi-calculus/join-calculus] The join-calculus programming language is a new language based on the join-calculus process calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/join-calculus] It is implemented as an interpreter written in OCaml, and supports statically typed distributed programming, transparent remote communication, agent-based mobility, and some failure-detection.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] In computer science, a **mobile agent** is a piece of software agent combined with data that is able to migrate from one computer to another autonomously and continue its execution on the destination with the ability to interact with other agents there.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] Rather than a client requesting data and performing actions, a mobile agent is sent to a server to perform those tasks.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] This paradigm delegates the work from the client and onto the server.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] A *mobile agent* is a type of software agent, with the feature of *autonomy*, *social ability*, *learning*, and most significantly, *mobility*.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] More specifically, a mobile agent is a process that can transport its state from one environment to another, with its data intact, and be capable of performing appropriately in the new environment.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] Mobile agents decide when and where to move.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] Movement is often evolved from RPC methods.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] Just as a user directs a web browser to "visit" a website (the browser merely downloads a copy of the site, or one version of it in the case of dynamic web sites), a mobile agent accomplishes a move through data duplication.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] When a mobile agent decides to move, it saves its own state (process image), transports this saved state to the new host and resumes execution from the saved state.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] A mobile agent is a specific form of mobile code, within the field of code mobility.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] However, in contrast to the remote evaluation and code on demand programming paradigms, mobile agents are active in that they can *choose* to migrate between computers at any time during their execution.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] This makes them a powerful tool for implementing distributed applications in a computer network.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] The classification is based on their migration path.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] Free roaming mobile agent: these have a dynamic migration path.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] Depending on the present network condition, the mobile agent chooses its path.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] An open multi-agent system (MAS) is a system in which agents, that are owned by a variety of stakeholders, continuously enter and leave the system.
[src:pi-calculus/mobile-agent] One particular advantage for remote deployment of software includes increased portability thereby making system requirements less influential.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] In computer science and computer programming, a **nondeterministic algorithm** is an algorithm that, even for the same input, can exhibit different behaviors on different runs, as opposed to a deterministic algorithm.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] Explicit algorithms using randomness were considered before formalizing the concept of nondeterminism in computer science.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] Pocklington introduced a randomized algorithm known as Pocklington's algorithm for efficiently finding square roots modulo prime numbers.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] In the 1930s, Enrico Fermi experimented with the Monte Carlo method while studying neutron diffusion, but he did not publish this work.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] Scientists at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in the 1940s and 50s developed and implemented the concept leading to the first publications concerned with Monte Carlo algorithms.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] Rabin and Dana Scott introduced and formalized nondeterministic finite automatons (NFA) in 1959.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] In that paper they show the equivalence to deterministic finite automatons (DFA) in terms of the ability to recognize languages.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] They also apply them to Turing machines (TM) thereby introducing nondeterministic Turing machines (NTM).
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] Using NFAs they could reprove in a more streamlined way certain closure properties of regular languages previously established by Stephen C.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] The term *nondeterministic algorithm* was used by Robert W.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] The paper uses the graphical language of flow charts which is a different way to formalize algorithms compared to automata or Turing machines and at that time was closer to the practice of programming on electronic computers.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] In philosophy ideas revolving around determinism vs. free will go back at least to ancient Greece.
[src:pi-calculus/nondeterministic-algorithm] In particular because of this additional property nondeterminism in computer science constitutes a new development compared to nondeterminism in traditional philosophy.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In theoretical computer science, the **π-calculus** (or **pi-calculus**) is a process calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The π-calculus allows channel names to be communicated along the channels themselves, and in this matter, it is able to describe concurrent computations whose network configuration may change during the computation.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The π-calculus has few terms and is a small, yet expressive language (see § Syntax).
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Functional programs can be encoded into the π-calculus, and the encoding emphasises the dialogue nature of computation, drawing connections with game semantics.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Extensions of the π-calculus, such as the spi calculus and applied π, have been successful in reasoning about cryptographic protocols.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Beside the original use in describing concurrent systems, the π-calculus has also been used to reason through business processes, molecular biology. and autonomous agents in artificial intelligence.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The π-calculus belongs to the family of process calculi, mathematical formalisms for describing and analyzing properties of concurrent computation.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In fact, the π-calculus, like the λ-calculus, is so minimal that it does not contain primitives such as numbers, Booleans, data structures, variables, functions, or even the usual control flow statements (such as `if-then-else`, `while`).
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Central to the π-calculus is the notion of *name*.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The simplicity of the calculus lies in the dual role that names play as *communication channels* and *variables*.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Although the minimalism of the π-calculus prevents us from writing programs in the normal sense, it is easy to extend the calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In particular, it is easy to define both control structures such as recursion, loops and sequential composition and datatypes such as first-order functions, truth values, lists and integers.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Moreover, extensions of the π-calculus have been proposed which take into account distribution or public-key cryptography.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The *applied π-calculus* due to Abadi and Fournet put these various extensions on a formal footing by extending the π-calculus with arbitrary datatypes.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Below is a tiny example of a process which consists of three parallel components.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The channel name x is only known by the first two components.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The first two components are able to communicate on the channel x, and the name y becomes bound to z.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Note that the remaining y is not affected because it is defined in an inner scope.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The second and third parallel components can now communicate on the channel name z, and the name v becomes bound to x.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Note that since the local name x has been output, the scope of x is extended to cover the third component as well.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Finally, the channel x can be used for sending the name x.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Let Χ be a set of objects called *names*.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In the concrete syntax below, the prefixes bind more tightly than the parallel composition (|), and parentheses are used to disambiguate.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Names are bound by the restriction and input prefix constructs.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Formally, the set of free names of a process in π–calculus are defined inductively by the table below.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The set of bound names of a process are defined as the names of a process that are not in the set of free names.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Central to both the reduction semantics and the labelled transition semantics is the notion of **structural congruence**.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Two processes are structurally congruent, if they are identical up to structure.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In particular, parallel composition is commutative and associative.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This last axiom is known as the "scope extension" axiom.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This axiom is central, since it describes how a bound name x may be extruded by an output action, causing the scope of x to be extended.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In cases where x is a free name of Q , alpha-conversion may be used to allow extension to proceed.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] We write $P\rightarrow P'$ if P can perform a computation step, following which it is now $P'$ .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This *reduction relation* $\rightarrow$ is defined as the least relation closed under a set of reduction rules.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] would not be free, alpha-conversion may be required.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This rule says that parallel composition does not inhibit computation.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This rule ensures that computation can proceed underneath a restriction.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The latter rule states that processes that are structurally congruent have the same reductions.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Note how, applying the reduction substitution axiom, free occurrences of y are now labeled as z .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This was captured using the scope extension axiom.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Alternatively, one may give the pi-calculus a labelled transition semantics (as has been done with the Calculus of Communicating Systems).
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Where states P and $P'$ represent processes and $\alpha$ is either an *input action* $a(x)$ , an *output action* *${\overline {a}}\langle x\rangle$*, or a *silent action* τ.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The syntax given above is a minimal one.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] However, the syntax may be modified in various ways.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] A *nondeterministic choice operator* $P+Q$ can be added to the syntax.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] A test for *name equality* $[x=y]P$ can be added to the syntax.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This *match operator* can proceed as P if and only if x and y are the same name.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Similarly, one may add a *mismatch operator* for **name inequality**.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Practical programs which can pass names (URLs or pointers) often use such functionality: for directly modeling such functionality inside the calculus, this and related extensions are often useful.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The *asynchronous π-calculus* allows only outputs with no continuation, i.e. output atoms of the form ${\overline {x}}\langle y\rangle$ , yielding a smaller calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] However, any process in the original calculus can be represented by the smaller asynchronous π-calculus using an extra channel to simulate explicit acknowledgement from the receiving process.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Since a continuation-free output can model a message-in-transit, this fragment shows that the original π-calculus, which is intuitively based on synchronous communication, has an expressive asynchronous communication model inside its syntax.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The *polyadic π-calculus* allows communicating more than one name in a single action: ${\overline {x}}\langle z_{1},...,z_{n}\rangle .P$ *(polyadic output)* and $x(z_{1},...,z_{n}).P$ *(polyadic input)*.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This polyadic extension, which is useful especially when studying types for name passing processes, can be encoded in the monadic calculus by passing the name of a private channel through which the multiple arguments are then passed in sequence.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] All other process constructs are left unchanged by the encoding.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In the above, $[P]$ denotes the encoding of all prefixes in the continuation P in the same way.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The full power of replication $!P$ is not needed.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Often, one only considers *replicated input* $!x(y).P$ , whose structural congruence axiom is $!x(y).P\equiv x(y).P|!x(y).P$ .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Replicated input process such as $!x(y).P$ can be understood as servers, waiting on channel x to be invoked by clients.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Invocation of a server spawns a new copy of the process $P[a/y]$ , where a is the name passed by the client to the server, during the latter's invocation.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] A *higher order π-calculus* can be defined where not only names but processes are sent through channels.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Here, Y denotes a *process variable* which can be instantiated by a process term.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Sangiorgi established that the ability to pass processes does not increase the expressivity of the π-calculus: passing a process *P* can be simulated by just passing a name that points to *P* instead.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The π-calculus is a universal model of computation.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This was first observed by Milner in his paper "Functions as Processes", in which he presents two encodings of the lambda-calculus in the π-calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] One encoding simulates the eager (call-by-value) evaluation strategy, the other encoding simulates the normal-order (call-by-name) strategy.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In both of these, the crucial insight is the modeling of environment bindings – for instance, "x is bound to term ${\textstyle M}$ " – as replicating agents that respond to requests for their bindings by sending back a connection to the term M .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The features of the π-calculus that make these encodings possible are name-passing and replication (or, equivalently, recursively defined agents).
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In the absence of replication/recursion, the π-calculus ceases to be Turing-complete.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This can be seen by the fact that bisimulation equivalence becomes decidable for the recursion-free calculus and even for the finite-control π-calculus where the number of parallel components in any process is bounded by a constant.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] As for process calculi, the π-calculus allows for a definition of bisimulation equivalence.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In the π-calculus, the definition of bisimulation equivalence (also known as bisimilarity) may be based on either the reduction semantics or on the labelled transition semantics.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] There are (at least) three different ways of defining *labelled bisimulation equivalence* in the π-calculus: Early, late and open bisimilarity.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] This stems from the fact that the π-calculus is a value-passing process calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In the remainder of this section, we let p and q denote processes and R denote binary relations over processes.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Early and late bisimilarity were both formulated by Milner, Parrow and Walker in their original paper on the π-calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Processes p and q are said to be early bisimilar, written $p\sim _{e}q$ if the pair $(p,q)\in R$ for some early bisimulation R .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In late bisimilarity, the transition match must be independent of the name being transmitted.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Processes p and q are said to be late bisimilar, written $p\sim _{l}q$ if the pair $(p,q)\in R$ for some late bisimulation R .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Both $\sim _{e}$ and $\sim _{l}$ suffer from the problem that they are not *congruence relations* in the sense that they are not preserved by all process constructs.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] More precisely, there exist processes p and q such that $p\sim _{e}q$ but $a(x).p\not \sim _{e}a(x).q$ .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] One may remedy this problem by considering the maximal congruence relations included in $\sim _{e}$ and $\sim _{l}$ , known as *early congruence* and *late congruence*, respectively.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Fortunately, a third definition is possible, which avoids this problem, namely that of *open bisimilarity*, due to Sangiorgi.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Processes p and q are said to be open bisimilar, written $p\sim _{o}q$ if the pair $(p,q)\in R$ for some open bisimulation R .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Early, late and open bisimilarity are distinct.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The containments are proper, so $\sim _{o}\subsetneq \sim _{l}\subsetneq \sim _{e}$ .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In certain subcalculi such as the asynchronous pi-calculus, late, early and open bisimilarity are known to coincide.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] However, in this setting a more appropriate notion is that of *asynchronous bisimilarity*.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In the literature, the term *open bisimulation* usually refers to a more sophisticated notion, where processes and relations are indexed by distinction relations; details are in Sangiorgi's paper cited above.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Alternatively, one may define bisimulation equivalence directly from the reduction semantics.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] We write $p\Downarrow a$ if process p immediately allows an input or an output on name a .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] We say that p and q are *barbed bisimilar* if there exists a barbed bisimulation R where $(p,q)\in R$ .
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Defining a context as a π term with a hole [] we say that two processes P and Q are *barbed congruent*, written $P\sim _{b}Q\,\!$ , if for every context $C[]$ we have that $C[P]$ and $C[Q]$ are barbed bisimilar.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] It turns out that barbed congruence coincides with the congruence induced by early bisimilarity.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The π-calculus has been used to describe many different kinds of concurrent systems.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In fact, some of the most recent applications lie outside the realm of traditional computer science.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In 1997, Martin Abadi and Andrew Gordon proposed an extension of the π-calculus, the Spi-calculus, as a formal notation for describing and reasoning about cryptographic protocols.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The spi-calculus extends the π-calculus with primitives for encryption and decryption.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In 2001, Martin Abadi and Cedric Fournet generalised the handling of cryptographic protocols to produce the applied π calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] There is now a large body of work devoted to variants of the applied π calculus, including a number of experimental verification tools.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] One example is the tool ProVerif due to Bruno Blanchet, based on a translation of the applied π-calculus into Blanchet's logic programming framework.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Another example is Cryptyc , due to Andrew Gordon and Alan Jeffrey, which uses Woo and Lam's method of correspondence assertions as the basis for type systems that can check for authentication properties of cryptographic protocols.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Around 2002, Howard Smith and Peter Fingar became interested that π-calculus would become a description tool for modeling business processes.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] By July 2006, there is discussion in the community about how useful this would be.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Most recently, the π-calculus has formed the theoretical basis of Business Process Modeling Language (BPML), and of Microsoft's XLANG.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The π-calculus has also attracted interest in molecular biology.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In 1999, Aviv Regev and Ehud Shapiro showed that one can describe a cellular signaling pathway (the so-called RTK/MAPK cascade) and in particular the molecular "lego" which implements these tasks of communication in an extension of the π-calculus.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] Following this seminal paper, other authors described the whole metabolic network of a minimal cell.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In 2009, Anthony Nash and Sara Kalvala proposed a π-calculus framework to model the signal transduction that directs *Dictyostelium discoideum* aggregation.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] The π-calculus was originally developed by Robin Milner, Joachim Parrow and David Walker in 1992, based on ideas by Uffe Engberg and Mogens Nielsen.
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] It can be seen as a continuation of Milner's work on the process calculus CCS (Calculus of Communicating Systems).
[src:pi-calculus/π-calculus] In his Turing lecture, Milner describes the development of the π-calculus as an attempt to capture the uniformity of values and processes in actors.
